England":"Tormohun, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Briwere","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Pierre, Adrien, Aurele, Benedicte, Benoit, Colette, Fernand, Gaston, Marcel, Micheline.","French (<b>Brière</b>): topographic name from a regional variant of Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heather’ (see   Bruyere  ), or a habitational name from La Brière, the name of several places mainly in the northern part of France, from the same word.","History: Jean Brière from Clarbec in Calvados, France, married Jeanne Grandin in Quebec City, QC, in 1671."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruyere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Fernand, Jacques, Marcel.","French (<b>Bruyère</b>): from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heather’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived in a place where heather grew, or a habitational name from one of the places in France (for example in Calvados) named with this word. Compare   Labruyere  .","Altered form (<b>Bruyère</b>) of French <b>Bruguier</b>: habitational name from (Le) Bruguier, the name of several places in the southeastern part of France, a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William de Briwere Heiress of Torre Brewer was born about 1090, in Tormohun, Devon, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with William de Briwere I. She died in 1121, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1090–1121":"umbes 1090–1121","1086–1115":"1086–1115","1114–1205":"1114–1205","1090–1121":"1090–1121","1090":"1090","1205":"1205","1115":"1115","about 1090":"umbes 1090","1114":"1114","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","Torre, Devonshire, England":"Torquay, Devon, England","Torre Brewer Manor, Tormohun, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Torres Brewer Manor, Tormohum, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1090–1121":"noin 1090–1121","1086–1115":"1086–1115","1114–1205":"1114–1205","1090–1121":"1090–1121","1090":"1090","1205":"1205","1115":"1115","about 1090":"noin 1090","1114":"1114","1121":"1121","1086":"1086","Torre, Devonshire, England":"Torquay, Devon, England","Torre Brewer Manor, Tormohun, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Torres Brewer Manor, Tormohum, Devon, England":"Tormohun, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1090–1121":"environ 1090–1121","1086–1115":"1086–1115","1114–1205":"1114–1205","1090–112